ry VI and the Politics of Kingship |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-42039-6 |url={{google books|qTP4CF_boeoC|plainurl=yes}} |authorlink=John Watts (historian) |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite IrishBio |subpage=York, Richard, Duke of |page=575 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last= Weir |date=1996 |first=A. |title=The Wars of the Roses |url=https://erenow.com/postclassical/lancasterandyork/ |authorlink=Alison Weir |postscript=. First published in 1995 as ''Lancaster & York''.|ref=harv }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{britannica|653703|Richard, 3rd duke of York}}\n* {{cite web |editor-last=Lundy |editor-first=Darryl |title=Richard Plantagenet, 3rd Duke of York |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p10164.htm#i101632 |website=The Peerage }}<!-- |accessdate=1 June 2007-->\n* {{cite web |title=Richard, Duke of York |url=http://www.luminarium.org/encyclopedia/richardyork.htm|website=Luminarium Encyclopedia }}<!-- |accessdate=23 April 2018-->\n* {{cite web |title=Richard Plantagenet, Duke of York |url= http://www.shakespeareandhistory.com/richard-plantagenet-duke-of-york.php |website=Shakespeareandhistory.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911024813/http://www.shakespeareandhistory.com/richard-plantagenet-duke-of-york.php |archivedate=11 September 2017 }}\n* {{cite web |title=The myth of \"Joan of York\" or \"Joan Plantagenet\" |date=26 April 2017 |url=https://riiiresearch.blogspot.co.uk/2017/04/the-myth-of-joan-of-york-or-joan.html |website=Richard III Society Research blog }} By a committee chaired by [[J. L. Laynesmith|Joanna Laynesmith]].\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[House of York]]|21 September|1411|30 December|1460|[[House of Plantagenet]]}}\n{{S-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester|The Duke of Gloucester]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Justice in eyre]] south&nbsp;of the [[River Trent|Trent]]|years=1447\u20131453}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Edmund Beaufort, 2nd Duke of Somerset|The Duke of Somerset]]}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John, Duke of Bedford|The Duke of Bedford]]|as=regent}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Lieutenant-general of France|years=1436\u20131437}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Richard Beauchamp, 13th Earl of Warwick|The Earl of Warwick]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Beaufort, 1st Duke of Somerset|The Earl of Somerset]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Lieutenant-general of France|years=1440\u20131445}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Edmund Beaufort, 1st Duke of Somerset|The Marquess of Dorset]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Talbot, 1st Earl of Shrewsbury|The Earl of Shrewsbury]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of chief governors of Ireland|Lieutenant of Ireland]]|years=1447\u20131460}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Plantagenet, Duke of Clarence|The Duke of Clarence]]}}\n{{S-reg|en}}\n|-\n{{S-bef | before=[[Edward, 2nd Duke of York|Edward]]}}\n{{S-ttl | title=[[Duke of York]]| years=1415\u20131460}}\n{{S-aft | after=[[Edward IV of England|Edward Plantagenet]] | rows=3}}\n{{S-bef | before=[[Richard of Conisburgh, 3rd Earl of Cambridge|Richard of Conisburgh]]}}\n{{S-ttl | title=[[Earl of Cambridge]] | years=1415\u20131460}}\n{{S-bef | before=[[Edmund Mortimer, 5th Earl of March|Edmund Mortimer]]}}\n{{S-ttl | title=[[Earl of March]] | years=1425\u20131460}}\n{{S-reg|ie}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Edmund Mortimer, 5th Earl of March|Edmund Mortimer]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Earl of Ulster]]|years=1425\u20131460}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Edward IV of England|Edward Plantagenet]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Princes of Wales}}\n{{Dukes of York|Richard Plantagenet}}\n{{Wars of the Roses}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richard, 3rd Duke of York}}\n[[Category:1411 births]]\n[[Category:1460 deaths]]\n[[Category:15th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Church of Saint Mary and All Saints, Fotheringhay]]\n[[Category:Dukes of York]]\n[[Category:Earls of March (1328)|Plantagenet]]\n[[Category:Earls of Ulster (1264)|Plantagenet]]\n[[Category:English military personnel killed in action]]\n[[Category:English people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Heirs to the English throne]]\n[[Category:House of York]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Lords Lieutenant of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Lords Protector of England]]\n[[Category:People of the Hundred Years' War]]\n[[Category:People of the Wars of the Roses]]\n[[Category:Pretenders to the English throne]]\n[[Category:Princes of Wales]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n", "name_user": "Heatherceana", "label": "safe", "comment": "The date of birth is always given as the 21st of Sep, 1411.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_of_York,_3rd_Duke_of_York"}
{"title_page": "Elizabeth Thompson (painter)", "text_new": "{{short description|American painter}}\n[[File:Elizabeth Thompson.jpg|thumb]]\n'''Elizabeth Thompson''' (born 1954 in [[New York City]]) is an American painter whose works have been described by writer and art historian [[Bonnie Clearwater]] as \"a call to action for the reclamation of Paradise\". She has painted the Florida [[Everglades]] as \"de-peopled visions of a primordial Eden.\"<ref>Bonnie Clearwater: \u201cElizabeth Thompson\u2019s Enchated Forest\u201d, Elizabeth Thompson Forty Years of Painting, Coral Springs Museum of Art</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Helander |first1=Bruce |title=Ever-Present, Effervescent, Everglades |url=https://issuu.com/arthivemagazine/docs/arthivefall_23/26?ff=true |accessdate=11 March 2020 |issue=23 |publisher=Art Hive |date=2017}}</ref> Thompson lives in Florida and New York City.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nThompson grew up in [[Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey|Englewood Cliffs]] New Jersey. Thompson received a BA from [[Mount Holyoke College]] and graduated Magna Cum Laude in 1975. [[Pratt Institute]] awarded her a BFA in 1977. She attended the [[\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure des Beaux-Arts|Ecole des Beaux Arts]] in [[Paris]] from 1976-77.\n\n== Career ==\nThompson began her carer by winning a competition to paint 135 oil storage tanks on the New Jersey side of the [[Hudson River]]. She then went to Paris and had her first exhibit on the Rue Seine in 1978. She has an extensive list of site specific murals that were commissioned by corporations and collectors. She also painted series that include subjects such as Paris monuments and sphinxes, swimming pools at night, African landscapes, the Everglades and impending environmental events.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://elizabeththompsonart.com/paris/|title=Paris|last=|first=|date=|website=Elizabeth Thompson Art|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> [[Bruce Helander]], in the introduction to the book that accompanied her exhibition at the [[Coral Springs Museum of Art]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://coralspringsmuseum.org/elizabeth-thompson/|title=40 Years of Painting|last=Thompson|first=Elizabeth|date=|website=Coral Springs Museum of Art|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> says \"Thompson's a visual storyteller whose canvases are filled with plot-twists.\"<ref>Bruce Helander,\u201dEvery Picture Tells a Story\u201d, Elizabeth Thompson Forty Years of Painting, Coral Srings Museum of Art</ref> Thompson has had 17 solo exhibitions and has participated in 16 group exhibitions. She cocurrated an exhibition \"Pools\" that toured gallery and museum venues worldwide, including at a Gallery in [[Moscow]], Russia in 1989.This exhibition was the first independent show in a nongovernment gallery in Moscow since 1917. At an exhibition of her Africa paintings,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://elizabeththompsonart.com/africa/|title=Africa|last=|first=|date=|website=Elizabeth Thompson Art|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> some visitors commented that the landscapes reminded them of the Everglades. After floating through a tunnel of Mangroves, she was hooked. Critic Jon Thomasson wrote of her palette, \"you discover shades of green you didn't know existed\".<ref>John Thomasson, \u201cWhere the Wild Things Are:An Elizabeth Thompson Retrospective\u201d Boca Magazine, Feb 1, 2019</ref>\n\n== Style ==\n[[File:Purple Chairs.jpg|thumb|Purple Chairs, 2014 Oil on Canvas 48\" x 75\u201d]]\n[[File:Cacti Forever.jpg|thumb|Cacti Forever, \u00a02016, Acrylic and Oil on Canvas,58\" x 69\u201d]]\n[[File:Homage to Hokusai.jpg|thumb|Homage to Hokusai. 2019,Acrylic on Canvas, 59\u201d x 73]]\nThompson uses both the traditional method of [[Oil paint|oil]] and canvas, but beginning in 2017 began experimenting with [[Acrylic paint|acrylics]] on unprimed canvas. She paints on the floor and allows the \"accidents\" created by pouring paint directly on the canvas dictate the eventual subject and composition of the work. \n\n== Personal life ==\nThompson married Richard Thompson in 1978 and was widowed in 2006. She now lives with her partner, Guerrino De Luca. She has two daughters, Victoria Thompson and Antonia Thompson Weisman.\n\n== Solo exhibitions ==\n* 1974 Mount Holyoke College Museum, Massachusetts.\n* 1977 Pratt Institute Gallery, New York.\n* 1978 Galerie Les Arts Plastiques Modernes, Paris.\n* 1979 Plan Gallery, Knokke-Le-Zoute, Belgium.\n* 1983 Andrew Crispo Gallery, New York.\n* 1989 Galeria Lavignes-Bastile, Paris / Albemarle Gallery, London.\n* 1990 Barbara Gilman Gallery, Miami, Florida.\n* 1993 John Harms Center, Englewood, New Jersey.\n* 1996 Art Miami, Miami, Florida / Adamar Fine Arts, Miami, Florida / Caesarea Gallery, Boca Raton, Florida.\n* 2001 Walter Wickiser Gallery, New York, New York / Sommerhill Gallery, Durham, North Carolina.\n* 2004 Walter Wickiser Gallery, New York, New York.\n* 2006 Leila Taghinia-Milani Heller Gallery, New York.\n* 2009 Leila Heller Gallery, New York.\n* 2012 Leila Heller Gallery, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.leilahellergallery.com/exhibitions/elizabeth-thompson-stories-from-the-everglades?view=slider#5|title=Stories from the Everglades|last=|first=|date=|website=Leila Heller Gallery|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n* 2013 Pop Up Show Royal Poinciana Plaza, Florida.\n* 2015 Capitol ExhibitionGallery,Florida Division of Cultural Affairs, Tallahassee, Florida.\n* 2019 \"40 Years of Painting\", Coral Springs Museum of Art, Coral Springs, Florida.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* 2015 Capitol Exhibition, Tallahassee.\n\n== Group exhibitions ==\n* 1981 Six at Mount Holyoke College Museum, Massachusetts.\n* 1982 \"Selected 20th Century American Painting & Sculpture,\" / Andrew Crispo Gallery, New York / \"Collectors Gallery 16,\" McKay Art Museum, San Antonio, Texas.\n* 1983 \"Selected 20th Century American Painting & Sculpture,\" / Andrew Crispo Gallery, New York.\n* 1988 \"New York - New Works,\" Helande Gallery, Palm Beach, Florida.\n* 1990 \"Pools\", Modus Vivendi Gallery, Zurich, Switzerland / \"Pools\", Art Moderne Gallery, Moscow, Russia / \"Pools\", Norton Museum, West Palm Beach, Florida.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://elizabeththompsonart.com/pools/|title=Pools|last=|first=|date=|website=Elizabeth Thompson Art|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n* 1991 \"Nuptuals\", Helander Gallery, New York / \"Pools\", Stuart Levy Gallery, New York / \"Pools\", Stuart Levy and Helander Galleries, New York City.\n* 1992 Helander Gallery, Palm Beach, Florida / \"Pools\", Aspen Art Museum, Aspen, Colorado.\n* 1996 Art Miami, Miami, Florida / Adamar Fine Arts, Miami, Florida / Caesarea Gallery, Boca Raton, Florida.\n* 2005 Art Miami, Miami, Florida / Adamar Fine Arts, Miami, Florida.\n* 2008 Scope Art Fair Miami, Leila Taghinia-Milani Heller Gallery, New York.\n* 2010 Tripoli Gallery, South Hampton.\n* 2010 Miami International Airport.\n* 2012 Art Basel, (Art Miami) Leila Heller Gallery.\n \n== Awards and honors ==\n* 1974 Janet F. Brooks Memorial Prize in Painting.\n* 1975 Phi Beta Kappa Award.\n* 1976-77 Skinner Foundation Fellowship.\n* 1977-78 Rotary Foundation Fellowship.\n* 1979-81 Artist in Residence, Centre Georges Pompidou, Paris.\n* 1984-86 Artist in Residence, PS 1, Queens, New York.\n* 2006 Artist in Residence, Everglades National Park, Florida.\n* 2009 National Organization of Women, NOW award for Women of Power and Substance.\n\n== Commissions ==\n* 1975 Mural Commission for Village in the Park, Chicago, Illinois / Hotel, Stamford, Connecticut.\n* 1976 Conversion of 135 oil storage tanks into a work of art. 300,000 square feet on the bank of the Hudson River, Commissioned by Belfer Associates and Prudential Insurance Company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://elizabeththompsonart.com/murals/|title=Murals - \"Oil Tanks\"|last=Thompson|first=Elizabeth|date=|website=elizabeththompsonart.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n* 1977 Mural Commission for the Rosalie Clinic, Aubervilliers.\n* 1981 Mural Commission for the Earl of Suffolk and Berkshire Charlton Park, Malmesbury, England.\n* 1983 Mural Commission for the Wilmington Trust Company, Wilmington, Delaware.\n* 1984 Mural Commission for Southwestern Bell Telephone, Dallas, Texas.\n* 1985 Triptych for Lincoln Properties, Dallas, Texas.\n* 1986 Two murals commissioned for the Club Corporation of America, Dallas, Texas.\n* 1989 Mural Commission for Robert Wood Johnson IV, Rockefeller Center, New York.\n* 1990 Mural Commission for the Association to Benefit Children, New York / Mural Commission for Mr. and Mrs. Tom Wolfe, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://elizabeththompsonart.com/murals/|title=Murals - \" Let It Shine\"|last=Thompson|first=Elizabeth|date=|website=elizabeththompsonart.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n* 1991 Mural Commission for Mr. and Mrs. Robert Wood Johnson IV for \"The Farm\", Lammington, New Jersey.\n* 1993 Mural Commission for El Grupo Financiero Asemex Banpais, Mexico City.\n* 1994 Second Mural Commission for El Grupo Financiero Asemex Banpais, Mexico City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://elizabeththompsonart.com/murals/|title=Murals - \"El Angel de Mexico\"|last=Thompson|first=Elizabeth|date=|website=elizabeththompsonart.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n* 1995 Mural Commission for the Delaware Water Authority, Delaware Memorial Bridge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://elizabeththompsonart.com/murals/|title=Elizabeth Thompson \u2013 Murals|website=elizabeththompsonart.com|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n* 1996 Mural aboard Ferry Boat for the Delaware Water Authority Mural on fa\u00e7ade of five-story building for the Association To Benefit Children.\n* 1997 Mural Commission for Marriott Shanghai Tang Emporium, First National Bank of Florida.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://elizabeththompsonart.com/murals/|title=Murals - \" Shanghai Tang\"|last=Thompson|first=Elizabeth|date=|website=elizabeththompsonart.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n* 1998 Mural Commission for New York University Hospital, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://elizabeththompsonart.com/murals/|title=Murals - \" New York University Hospital Oncology Entrance\"|last=Thompson|first=Elizabeth|date=|website=elizabeththompsonart.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n* 2000 Mural Commission for the Board Room of Metropolitan Life Insurance Company, New York.\n* 2003 Mural Commission for Mr. and Mrs. Glen Dubin, New York.\n\n== Collections ==\n* McKay Art Museum, San Antonio, Texas.\n* Museum of Modern Art, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.leilahellergallery.com/exhibitions/elizabeth-thompson-stories-from-the-everglades/selected-works?view=thumbnails|title=Stories from the Everglades - Exhibitions|last=|first=|date=|website=Leila Heller Gallery|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n* Coral Springs Museum of Art, Coral Springs, Florida.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Mr. and Mrs. Peter Brown.\n* Mr. Howard Gittis.\n* Mr. Itchko Ezratti.\n* Mrs. Francis Lloyd.\n* Weil, Gotschal and Manges, New York City.\n* Wells, Rich and Green, New York City.\n* Ingram Yusek, New York City.\n* Mr. and Mrs. Jonathan Hess.\n* Mr. Harry Joe Brown.\n* Dr. and Mrs. Patrick Stubgen.\n* Mr. and Mrs. Tom Wolfe.\n* Mr and Mrs William Rayner.\n\n== Bibliography  ==\n* {{official website|http://elizabeththompsonart.com/}}\n* [https://www.bocamag.com/where-the-wild-things-are-an-elizabeth-thompson-retrospective/ \"Where the Wild Things Are\"]\n* \"Elizabeth Thompson's Enchanted Forest\" Bonnie Clearwater for the catalog for \"Elizabeth Thompson, 40 Years of Painting\"\n* [h